<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
This American duckweed is a recent newcomer in the flora of the Canary Islands. It was first reported from several localities in Gran Canaria (
<bibRefCitation author="Verloove, F" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="59 - 82" refId="B6509955" refString="Verloove, F, 2013. New xenophytes from Gran Canaria (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species. Collectanea Botanica 32: 59 - 82" title="New xenophytes from Gran Canaria (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species" volume="32" year="2013">Verloove 2013</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Salas-Pascual, M" journalOrPublisher="Botanica Macaronesica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="73 - 81" refId="B6509509" refString="Salas-Pascual, M, Quintana Vega, G, 2016. Salvinia molesta D. S. Mitch. (Salviniaceae), nueva cita para Canarias y Espana. Botanica Macaronesica 29: 73 - 81" title="Salvinia molesta D. S. Mitch. (Salviniaceae), nueva cita para Canarias y Espana" volume="29" year="2016">Salas-Pascual and Quintana Vega 2016</bibRefCitation>
), subsequently also from La Palma (
<bibRefCitation author="Otto, R" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509407" refString="Otto, R, Verloove, F, 2020. New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species - Part 3. Collectanea Botanica 39" title="New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species - Part 3" volume="39" year="2020">Otto and Verloove 2020</bibRefCitation>
). It is a naturalised weed that also occurs in natural habitats. As it strongly resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Centricae" family="Chironomidae" genus="L." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. minor" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Diatomeae" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">L. minor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., it is undoubtedly overlooked. 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Centricae" family="Chironomidae" genus="L." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. minuta" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Diatomeae" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">L. minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is differentiated from the latter, based on the smaller fronds (even the largest are less than 3 mm long) with a single, slightly raised vein.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">In La Quinta, a small population was discovered in a seepage zone in 2018. It should be looked for elsewhere in the northern part of the Island.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kunth, 1815" authorityYear="1816" class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Lemnaceae" genus="Lemna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lemna minuta" order="Spathiflorae" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Lemna minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a well-known transformer species throughout the invaded range (
<bibRefCitation author="Paolacci, S" journalOrPublisher="Aquatic Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="8 - 14" refId="B6509416" refString="Paolacci, S, Harrison, S, Jansen, M A K, 2018. The invasive duckweed Lemna minuta Kunth displays a different light utilisation strategy than native Lemna minor Linnaeus. Aquatic Botany 146: 8 - 14" title="The invasive duckweed Lemna minuta Kunth displays a different light utilisation strategy than native Lemna minor Linnaeus" volume="146" year="2018">Paolacci et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
